sentences: Suzanne Haïk-Vantoura (née Vantoura; 13 July 1912 – 22 October 2000) was a French organist, music teacher, composer and music theorist.
Vantoura was born in Paris on 13 July 1912.
In 1931 Vantoura started studying at Conservatoire National Supérieur de Paris, (CNSMDP), and in 1934 earned a First Prize in Harmony.

Four years later, she was awarded a First Prize in Fugue (1938).

She was a pupil of the well-known organist and composer Marcel Dupré from 1941 to 1946.

She died on 22 October 2000 in Lausanne, Switzerland at the age of 88.
Her husband Maurice Haïk had died in 1976.
She was Honorary professor of music education (1937–61).
She was organist at the Synagogue de l'Union liberale Israelite de Paris (1946–53) and organist at the Église Saint-Hélène in Paris (1966–79).
